		<div class="container" style="padding: 0 1rem">
			<h2 id="Introduction">Introduction</h2>
			<p style="text-align: justify">
				Rare genetic diseases collectively affect more than 6% of the global population and skeletal disorders constitute
				an important group of these diseases. They often result in short stature, altered movement biomechanics, pain,
				fatigue, and reduced functional performance. They are individually very rare and are generally extremely
				heterogeneous. Therefore, even experienced clinicians might have seen only some of these disorders which makes
				their diagnosis a long and challenging process, sometimes referred to as the “diagnostic odyssey”.
			</p>
			<p style="text-align: justify">
				With the rapid development of artificial intelligence (AI), various medical imaging modalities can be used for
				developing next-generation phenotyping tools that are able to detect and recognize various and subtle
				dysmorphisms and features caused by different genetic diseases. Bone2Gene utilizes such AI techniques with
				the aim of shortening the “diagnostic odyssey”. We have so far collected 771 images of 189 patients with 7
				different skeletal disorders plus 79 healthy controls. The current data are from different clinics in Magdeburg
				and Leipzig in Germany.
			</p>
			<div  class="img">
				<ul id="statistics">
					<li><%= image_tag("patients_disorder_hist.jpg") %></li>
					<li><%= image_tag("pie.jpg") %></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<p style="text-align: justify">
				The current Bone2Gene classifier (so far trained on only 189 patients data) achieved an accuracy of 40% for 8
				different classes (random probability is 1/8 or 12.5%). With increasing the data and also the number of disorders,
				we envision Bone2Gene to become a supportive assistant to clinical geneticists. If you are interested in joining
				our effort or you can provide us with rare skeletal disorders data, please use the info below this page to get in
				touch with us.
			</p>
